IDA Project P095965: The Siddhirganj Peaking Power Project for Government of Bangladesh (GOB) aims to increase the supply of power during periods of peak demand in Bangladesh (GOB), and to strengthen the three implementing agencies: Gas Transmission Company Limited (GTCL), Electricity Generation Company of Bangladesh (EGCB), and Power Grid Company of Bangladesh (PGCB). 



The project will have five components: 

i) a 60-km natural gas pipeline from the gas processing center at Bakhrabad to the power generation site at Siddhirganj; 

ii) a 300MW peaking power plant at Siddhirganj, composed of simple-cycle gas turbines; 

iii) an 11-km, 230 kv transmission line from Siddhirganj to the Maniknagar grid substation in South Dhaka, plus associated switchgear;

iv) technical assistance to support the base fees of an operations and maintenance (O&M) contractor for the power plant, and owner's engineers for the GTCL and PGCB components; and 

v) core management information systems for GTCL and EGCB. 



The project aims to make a direct contribution to the country's economic growth, while also helping Bangladesh stabilize electricity supply, thereby supporting both the country's growth prospects and grid electrification program.

IFC Project 27250. The project will consist of a corporate loan to Corporacion Dinant S.A. de C.V. (‚ÄúDinant‚Äù), a vertically-integrated palm oil and food company in Honduras. The company is seeking funds primarily to: 



- increase production capacity in its snacks and edible oils divisions;

- expand and upgrade its distribution network;

- develop young palm oil plantations; and 

- build a biogas facility to generate electricity for own and third-party consumption.

IFC Project 26506. Green Resources ASA (GRAS) is implementing an investment program over the next three years to expand and modernize its saw mill operations in Sao Hill, Tanzania, and establish additional plantations in Tanzania, Uganda and Mozambique. The program will include: 



- achieving internationally recognized certifications including FSC, CDM and ISO 14001/9001; 

- planting 9,000 ha of land with eucalyptus, pine, teak and indigenous trees; 

- expanding its equipment for harvesting and wood transportation;

- modernizing an existing saw mill to increase efficiencies and capacity; 

- retrofitting a small wood waste to energy plant at the mill, and installing a new wood waste-fired Combined Heating and Power (CHP) facility; and

- associated, miscellaneous capital expenditures. 



GRAS‚Äôs plantation and wood waste-to-energy projects will address the issues created by deforestation by: 



- increasing the amount of trees planted every year, thereby functioning as a carbon sink,

- creating carbon offsets that will add to revenues,

- generating electricity from fuels produced by sustainably managed forests,

- providing a source of power poles for electric power distribution systems, and

- generating significant employment in rural areas for some of the poorest people in the countries where it operates. Approximately one person is employed for every plantation hectare planted. In addition, the increase in available electricity will decrease the demand for firewood, and will improve the living conditions of surrounding communities.

IDB Project CH-L1053. The goal of the Program is contribute to the institutional strengthening of Chile‚Äôs energy sector. The purpose is to support the Ministry of Energy‚Äôs effort to develop the new institutional framework and formulate a new energy sector strategy. Consequently, the Program will strengthen the main institutions linked to the energy sector (CNE, EECP, SEC, CChEN) by helping to design the Ministry of Energy‚Äôs strategy for coordination with the different agencies with authority

over energy matters. Its efforts will rest on four main pillars: security, efficiency, sustainability, and equity. The Program will lay the foundation for this new energy policy by supporting institutional adjustments and interventions to improve coordination in the sector. To the same end, it will also conduct studies and develop energy-matrix projection models based on the four pillars and the various possible scenarios. Activities to be carried out with the PROPEF funds are divided into three components: (i) support for the sector‚Äôs new institutional framework;

(ii) formulation of a new energy sector strategy; and (iii) creation of the Program Executing Unit. The electricity subsector matrix at the end of 2009 was composed of hydroelectric generation (38%) and thermoelectric generation (62%), mainly using open-cycle and combined-cycle natural gas plants (60%), coal-fired plants (26%), and diesel-fired plants (10%). The total cost of this project is $500,000.

EBRD Project Number 39579: This is financing for extension of the Georgian main 500kV system, with the addition of two new 500kV links from Gardabani and Zestaponi to a new 500kV substation near the Turkish border at Akhaltsikhe. Akhaltsikhe will be connected to the Turkish EHV grid at Borchka asynchronously using a Back-to-Back HVDC link at Akhaltsikhe. 



Implementation of the project will:



(i) Increase energy security and improve electricity balance between supply (generation located in the west part of the country) and demand (consumption areas mostly located in the east side of Georgia);



(ii) Stabilize the Georgian Electricity System;



(iii) Increase electricity trade in the Caucasus through the creation of an electricity hub for energy exchanges with neighboring countries;



(iv) Increase electricity exports to Turkey.



The borrower is the 100 percent state-owned Georgian State Electrosystem (GSE), with guarantee by the State of Georgia.



The project will be co-financed with the European Investment Bank and KfW. The total project cost is EUR 300 million, and the EBRD loan is EUR 80 million.

Project #43224- 01; The outcome of the TA will be the SAARC Energy Working Group recommendation on establishing a regional power exchange to the SAARC Energy Ministers. (i) A detailed review of the operations of the Indian Power Exchange analyzing the operating mechanisms and procedures that are followed and assessment of its performance and openings/opportunities for regional participation; 

(ii) Power System studies for different short/medium/long term scenarios to identify possible opportunities of power transfer and the necessary power transmission system modalities and requirements including associated costs and benefits; 

(iii) The institutional, regulatory and commercial arrangements that would be required and the procedure to set-up their arrangements; and 

(iv) A draft Inter-Governmental Agreement arranged for member states waiting to participate in a multilateral power market. This will cover the principles of electricity trade on which the participating member countries can plan and coordinate regional electricity transfer.

Description



    1) Building of a 9 km pipeline during the course of construction works on the East tramway in Paris, which will serve the 12th, 19th and 20th districts of the city and its immediate suburbs. This pipeline will render the La Villette plant obsolete as a heat generator and allow its demolition, the return of the site to the City of Paris, and the rezoning of four hectares of land for new housing, business areas, social and cultural amenities and green spaces;

    2) Increase of the share of renewables in CPCU‚Äôs energy mix through the construction of two deep geothermal heat plants in west Paris and in Ivry, south-east of Paris;

    3) upgrading of two CPCU oil-fired peak demand/emergency heating plants located in Vaugirard and Bercy to 2016 environmental standards by converting to gas, adding fume treatment devices to substantially cut emissions of pollutants (dust, sulphur and nitrogen oxides) or adding safety devices (control command).



Objectives



To develop district heating in east Paris, increase the share of renewables in the energy mix through the construction of two geothermal heat plants and upgrade oil-fired peak demand/emergency heating plants to 2016 environmental standards.

Project ID P103037: This financing is to support Kenya's Electricity Expansion Project to: (a) increase the capacity, efficiency, and quality of the electricity supply; and (b) expand access to electricity in urban, peri-urban, and rural areas. 



There are four components to the project;

I) Geothermal generation: this component will finance the construction of 280MWs of geothermal generation capacity, consisting of:    

   (i) a 140MW expansion of capacity of the existing first Olkaria power station; 

   (ii) construction of a new power station, Fourth Olkaria, with 140MW capacity; and 

   (iii) connection of steam wells to the two power stations and associated facilities for power transmission to the national grid. This component will also finance consulting services for design and supervision, and the installation of construction infrastructure and facilities required to operate the plants.



II) Transmission: This component includes construction of 132 kV transmission lines, as well as substations that step down the voltage from these lines to the distribution system. 



III) Distribution: The third component has four sub-components to support the expansion and upgrading of the distribution network, as well as connection of an additional 300,000 customers over the period of 2011-2016. 



IV) Sectoral institutional development and operational support.



The total project cost in USD is $1,390,650,000,000. 



Financing is broken down as follows: European Investment Bank: $168,000,000.00; French Agency for Development: $220,000,000.00, 

The International Development Association (IDA): $330,000,000.00; 

The German Kreditanstalt Fur Wiederaufbau (Kfw): $84,000,000.00; 

Local sources of borrowing country: $90,950,000.00; 

Japan International Cooperation Agency (Jica): $323,000,000.00; 

Borrower: $169,700,000.00, and 

Global Partnership on Output-Based Aid: $5,000,000.00.

Project ID P114204: The development objective of the Eletrobras Distribution Rehabilitation Project for Brazil is to improve the financial and operational performance and the commercial management of the six DisCos (Distribution Companies) by reducing electricity losses, increasing bill collection rates, and improving quality of service. 



There are two components to the project. The first component of the project is service quality improvement and loss reduction. This component improves the quality of service, reducing electricity losses and increasing collection rates in electricity distribution and retail through the acquisition of goods, equipment, works and services for the following activities: 

i) distribution network reinforcement; 

ii) implementation of Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) and other actions to maximize metered consumption; and 

iii) modernization of DisCos Management Information System (MIS). 



The second component of the project is institutional strengthening. This component strengthens the operational capacities of the DisCos through technical assistance, training, consultancy services, studies, equipment, and operational costs in the following areas: 

i) performance-based management including support for project implementation, monitoring, reporting and evaluation by the project management unit and the six DisCos;

ii) management of environmental and social impacts and processes;

iii) support for community outreach; and

iv) support to selected programs delivered at a sectoral training and research center in the guarantor's state of Acre.

